quran[10]{c,v,t}:
  27,89,"Whoever comes with a good deed—for him is one better than it and they are safe from <span class=""h"">horror<sup foot_note=""80761"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span><span class=""h"">on</span>that day,"
  27,90,"while whoever comes with an evil deed—their faces are tumbled into the Fire. “Are you{1}being repaid except for what you used to do?”",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from 3rd person to 2nd person.
  27,91,"<i class=""s"">(Say </i><a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a><i class=""s"">) </i>“Indeed, I have only been commanded to worship the Lord of this township, Who has made it inviolable and to Whom everything belongs, and I have been commanded to be of the Muslims{1}",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is Muslimeenwhich means those who willingly submit to God, regardless of which prophet they followed.
  27,92,"and to read the Recital{1}; so whoever is guided, then he is surely guided to his own benefit. And whoever goes astray, then say, “Indeed, I am only one of the forewarners.”",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is Qur’anwhich means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.
  27,93,"And say<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>, “Praise be to Allah; He will show you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>His signs and you will recognize them. For in no way is your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord oblivious of what <span class=""h"">you</span><a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a><span class=""h"">do<sup foot_note=""80765"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span>.”"
  28,1,"Tâ Sîn Mīm."
  28,2,"Those are the signs{1}of the Evident Scripture.",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used isayat(singularayah). Ayahmeans ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an,like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose.Each such unit isconsidered a ‘sign’from God.
  28,3,"We read to you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>from the tiding of Moses and Pharaoh in truth for people who believe."
  28,4,"Indeed, Pharaoh became exalted in the land and divided its people into sects, deeming a faction of them weak and oppressed: slaughtering their sons while keeping their women alive<i class=""s"">(in bondage) </i>. Indeed, he was one of the corrupters."
  28,5,"Thus We are willing to favor those who were deemed weak and oppressed in the land and to make them leaders and to make them the inheritors"
